Orchestrates the ctx-verify checkpoint: runs a fixed sequence of wrapped tools (`cargo fmt`, `clippy`, `doc`, `test`, plus repo scripts `rationale_check.py`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`, `no_allow_check.sh`, `machete_check.sh`) through a [`Runner`], parses each tool's output into diagnostics, caps them, and assembles one [`Report`].

`fmt` is listed first and is the only check that mutates the tree (it applies `cargo fmt --all`); every other check is report-only. Its parser (`noop_parser`) never emits diagnostics — fmt failures surface only via non-zero exit, caught generically by `run_spec`'s `failure_hint` fallback. That fallback fires for *any* check that fails but whose parser found nothing, guaranteeing no check ever produces a silent empty failure: it takes the last non-empty trimmed line from stderr (falling back to stdout) as a synthesized `Diagnostic` with lint `"exit"`.

`SPECS` is a static `&[Spec]` array — the definitive list and order of checks; adding a new check means adding a `Spec` entry with its own `Parser` fn. Each `Spec` pairs a tool/args/env with a `Parser = fn(&CommandOutcome) -> Vec<Diagnostic>`. `compiler_parser` expects clippy/rustdoc `--message-format=json` output (delegates to `parse::parse_compiler_json`). `script_parser` expects the script's combined stdout+stderr to contain `FAIL:`-prefixed lines (delegates to `parse::parse_fail_lines`) — the four bash/python scripts in `scripts/` must emit that exact prefix or their failures go unparsed (falling back to `failure_hint`). `test_parser` scans raw `cargo test` stdout/stderr line-by-line for substrings `"FAILED"` (suffix), `"error["` or `"error:"` (prefix) — not JSON, so it's fragile to cargo's human-format test output changing.

`effective_args(spec, package)` inserts `-p <package>` right after the subcommand (position 1) for cargo-tooled specs only; script-based checks ignore `package` entirely since they're repo-wide by nature.

`run_spec` distinguishes `CheckError::ToolMissing` (→ `CheckReport::skipped()`, e.g. tool not installed) from other spawn errors (→ `CheckReport::errored(...)`, carrying the message) from a successfully-run-but-failing check (→ `CheckReport::build` with diagnostics, capped at `max`). This three-way split matters to callers reading `Report`: `errored`/`skipped` are infra-level, not code failures.

`run_selected<R: Runner>(runner: &R, max: usize, only: Option<&[String]>, package: Option<&str>) -> Report` is the sole public entry point; `only` filters by `Spec.name` (None = run all in `SPECS` order, inserted into a `BTreeMap` so `Report` iterates alphabetically regardless of `SPECS` order). Depends on `crate::runner::Runner` trait for testability/mocking and `crate::parse` for the two JSON/text diagnostic parsers — coupling: if `parse::parse_compiler_json` or `parse::parse_fail_lines`'s expected formats drift from what clippy/rustdoc/scripts actually emit, diagnostics silently drop to zero (masked by the `failure_hint` fallback only on nonzero exit, not on success-with-warnings mismatches).